      children: "While in Cairo, Pederson purchased three appliqués; the one included in this exhibition depicts the Pyramids, the Sphinx, an obelisk, a palm tree, two camels, and two Egyptian men of non-elite background. The craft of appliqué has been practiced in Egypt since at least the medieval period, and has a dedicated market of artisans in one of the oldest parts of the city, known as “Suq al-Khayyamiyya” or “The Tentmakers Market.” This type of appliqué that depicts Pharaonic scenes was developed mainly for the emerging tourist market, while the more longstanding craft designs tended to be large and intricate geometric patterns often drawing on Islamic decorative designs. These were often done on a large scale to serve as panels for tents that, even today, are often erected for such social events as weddings, funerals, and saints-day festivals."
    }), "\n", _jsx(_components.p, {
